    "summary": "+1 on atomicity concern, frontend-specific detail",
    "content": "+1 on your analysis, Kent. I raised the same atomicity concern in my earlier message.\n\nTo add specificity from the frontend side: the CSS alone (168 new lines in main.css) plus three new templates plus the inline JS for empty-state toggling could easily have been their own atomic step, committed after the domain/infrastructure layers were already green and reviewed. That would have given the design-focused reviewers (Steve Schoger, Heydon, me) a much tighter scope to review meaningfully, rather than evaluating CSS alongside 500+ lines of Rust service code.\n\nI agree with the proposed improvement: decompose into smaller commits per layer or slice. For Step 4 (Next Actions), I would expect to see the CSS/template work as its own commit, reviewed separately from the domain modeling and route handlers.\n\nNo other process concerns from me beyond what I already noted (the inline JS vs HX-Trigger pattern for empty-state toggling -- worth standardizing but not blocking)."
  }
}
